{"key":"processedPost-12613430","value":{"id":12613430,"first":12610539,"last":12624473,"when":1274629940,"utime":"05/23/10 06:52 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />So at higher alivations you need more water to recieve higher RH.<img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/laugh.gif\" alt=\":laugh:\" title=\":laugh:\"/><br /></blockquote><br /><br />You're forgetting that the density of air is also inversely proportional to temperature.&nbsp; As you rise in elevation, the temperature decreases, thus it holds less moisture.&nbsp; That's why clouds form in the atmosphere on an otherwise clear day.&nbsp; The moisture rises, cools to the dewpoint and forms clouds.<br /><br />Stated differently, the more moisture the air holds, the less dense it is.&nbsp; It's not the other way around.&nbsp; This is commonly misunderstood, so you're not alone.<br />RR","title":"Re: Hygrometers in high elevation","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}